<paper id="1565378600"><title>Algorithms for Multi-exponentiation</title><year>2001</year><authors><author org="Technische Universität Darmstadt," id="2684758815">Bodo Möller</author></authors><n_citation>118</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1507106163</reference><reference>1521787982</reference><reference>1523099545</reference><reference>1539482743</reference><reference>1561590459</reference><reference>1570820619</reference><reference>1575893707</reference><reference>1591889770</reference><reference>1613874182</reference><reference>1660562555</reference><reference>2096369004</reference><reference>2108834246</reference><reference>2115190247</reference></references><venue id="2758123139" type="C">Selected Areas in Cryptography</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-45537-X_13</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.44698">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.49555">Commutative property</keyword><keyword weight="0.44537">Exponent</keyword><keyword weight="0.4296">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.47681">Cryptography</keyword><keyword weight="0.46248">Arithmetic</keyword><keyword weight="0.44134">Algorithm</keyword><keyword weight="0.50992">Public-key cryptography</keyword><keyword weight="0.69697">Exponentiation by squaring</keyword><keyword weight="0.63185">Exponentiation</keyword><keyword weight="0.47227">Elliptic curve</keyword><keyword weight="0.53315">Interleaving</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>This paper compares different approaches for computing power products Π1≤i≤k giei in commutative groups. We look at the conventional simultaneous exponentiation approach and present an alternative strategy, interleaving exponentiation. Our comparison shows that in general groups, sometimes the conventional method and sometimes interleaving exponentiation is more efficient. In groups where inverting elements is easy (e.g. elliptic curves), interleaving exponentiation with signed exponent 